  "prompt": "What is the curved surface area of a hemisphere?",
  "response": "The **curved surface area** of a hemisphere (which is half of a sphere) can be calculated using the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Curved Surface Area} = 2\\pi r^2\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( r \\) is the radius of the hemisphere.\n- \\( \\pi \\) (Pi) is approximately 3.14159.\n\n### Derivation:\n\n1. **Surface Area of a Full Sphere:**\n   \\[\n   \\text{Surface Area} = 4\\pi r^2\n   \\]\n   \n2. **Half of the Sphere (Hemisphere):**\n   - Since a hemisphere is half of a sphere, you might think to divide the surface area by 2:\n     \\[\n     \\frac{4\\pi r^2}{2} = 2\\pi r^2\n     \\]\n   - However, this only accounts for the curved surface and does **not** include the base (which is a flat circle with area \\(\\pi r^2\\)).\n   \n3. **Curved Surface Area Only:**\n   - Therefore, the curved surface area of the hemisphere is indeed:\n     \\[\n     2\\pi r^2\n     \\]\n\n### Example:\n\nIf the radius of the hemisphere is **5 cm**, then:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Curved Surface Area} = 2\\pi (5)^2 = 2\\pi \\times 25 = 50\\pi \\, \\text{cm}^2 \\approx 157.08 \\, \\text{cm}^2\n\\]\n\n### Summary:\n\n- **Curved Surface Area of a Hemisphere:** \\( 2\\pi r^2 \\)\n- **Total Surface Area (including base):** \\( 3\\pi r^2 \\) (where the base area \\(\\pi r^2\\) is added)\n\nMake sure to use the appropriate formula based on whether you need just the curved surface or the total surface area including the base.",
